<item>
            <title>[LU-7667] conf-sanity test_52 fails due to $TMP/files already existing</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-7667</link>
                <project id="10000" key="LU">Lustre</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;conf-sanity test 52 fails with &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&apos;Unable to create directory&apos; 
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Logs are at&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sets/3d0a4d2c-ba9d-11e5-87b4-5254006e85c2&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sets/3d0a4d2c-ba9d-11e5-87b4-5254006e85c2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;sanity test 51d writes the output of &#8216;lfs getstripe&#8217; for all files in $DIR/$tdir to a file $TMP/files and does not remove the file. When conf-sanity runs after sanity, conf-sanity test 52 tries to create a directory at $TMP/files and copy files into it. $TMP/files already exists and, thus, conf-sanity test 52 fails. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are at least two issues here. We should use a unique file or directory name based on the test being run and we should clean up $TMP after using it.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
